1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:23,160
Achird: Achird here. Welcome to State of Play, episode twenty-nine — and you'll hear me drop the "twenty-nine" rather than "twenty-something" because last week we renumbered the back catalogue into a single chronological sequence. So we're properly numbered now. Today's title: Pictures in Layers. Runtime: about fifty minutes — give or take three.

2
00:00:23,510 --> 00:01:13,790
Achird: Here's the shape of the next fifty minutes. Jacob asked us a deceptively simple question. He's got an upcoming Rotary Club of Port Pirie seventieth-anniversary slideshow, a fifteen-minute personal Rotary talk on Thursday this week, a clinical project called the Sepsis Poster Studio that already generates illustrations through an OpenAI image API, and a stack of other clinical communication deliverables — patient handouts, conference posters, infographics. He wants to know: which of these newly-released creativity tools should he actually use? Google Stitch. Google Flow. "ChatGPT Architecture AI" — whatever that is. ChatGPT Images Two. Claude Design. And the rest of the wave that's washed in over the past six months.

3
00:01:14,140 --> 00:01:39,780
Achird: We surveyed twenty-four tools. We talked through five major use-cases. And we landed on what I think is the most useful insight of the whole exercise — which is that the right answer for almost every creative project in May twenty-twenty-six is not one tool. It's three layers, each one served by a different specialist tool. That's the thesis of today's episode and the reason I picked the title.

4
00:01:40,130 --> 00:02:06,330
Achird: I'm hosting. Gacrux — strategy, the stack, the synergy. Laomedeia — design taste and aesthetic choices. Umbriel — the sceptic; he's going to make sure we don't fall for the launch hype. Zubenelgenubi — the clinician; he's the one keeping us honest about anatomical accuracy, identifiable-person risk, and Aboriginal data sovereignty. Alnilam closes us out at the end.

5
00:02:06,680 --> 00:02:15,400
Achird: Let's begin with the five tools Jacob named, because two of them have name ambiguity that we need to resolve before we can recommend anything.

6
00:02:15,750 --> 00:02:28,510
Gacrux: Gacrux here. I'll take the resolution. Two of the five names Jacob used don't resolve cleanly. We owe him an honest answer about what each one is before we recommend a workflow built on it.

7
00:02:28,860 --> 00:03:34,140
Gacrux: First — "ChatGPT Architecture AI." There is no OpenAI product in May twenty-twenty-six called "Architecture AI." There never has been. Three plausible interpretations. One — and this is the most plausible — Jacob means GPT-5.4 Thinking, which launched on the fifth of March. Its signature behaviour is to generate an upfront plan — an architecture of its reasoning — that the user can steer mid-response. Commentators commonly call this "architect mode." Two — there are third-party Custom GPTs in the GPT Store with names like ArchitectGPT and MyArchitectAI; these render building exteriors, interiors, floor plans, and have no clinical relevance. Three — the old Sora Architect feature; moot, because Sora was discontinued on the twenty-sixth of April. We're going with interpretation one. If Jacob actually meant interpretation two, the answer is straightforward: not relevant to any of his four use-cases.

8
00:03:34,490 --> 00:03:57,810
Gacrux: Second — "Claude Design." This resolved cleanly. It's an Anthropic Labs research-preview product, launched on the seventeenth of April, powered by Claude Opus 4.7. Bundled with every paid Claude tier — Pro, Max, Team, Enterprise. No separate purchase. Jacob is already on Claude Pro, so he already has access.

9
00:03:58,160 --> 00:04:29,920
Umbriel: Umbriel here. Just to push back gently — Anthropic calls Claude Design a "research preview." That phrase is doing real work. Features churn. The PPTX export pipeline drops gradients and shifts image crops, which means anything you build there and need to project in a venue needs final repair in Keynote or PowerPoint. Don't make it the sole layer on a time-critical deliverable. ### 1.2 Google Stitch — refreshed yesterday

10
00:04:30,270 --> 00:05:02,790
Laomedeia: Laomedeia here. Stitch is the one I keep getting questions about because Google has put a lot of marketing behind it. So let's be honest. Stitch is a UI and UX design tool. It takes a prompt and produces an app or web mockup. The output is editable in Figma, or it exports semantic HTML with Tailwind, React, Vue, Angular, Flutter, or SwiftUI. It is not a slide tool. It is not a poster tool. It is not a clinical-illustration tool.

11
00:05:03,140 --> 00:05:32,540
Laomedeia: What it's brilliant for — and this is a real thing — is when Jacob says, "I want to build a web page for a sepsis decision aid. What might it look like?" Stitch will give him a designed mock that an actual developer — or Alan Turing Ross in our family registry — can then turn into real code. For the four use-cases Jacob asked about, Stitch is wrong-tool for three of them and only useful for the fourth one in the narrow case of web-prototype mockups.

12
00:05:32,890 --> 00:05:54,210
Umbriel: And one important thing — Stitch was refreshed yesterday. Twentieth of May, at Google I/O. Stitch 2.0. Real-time streaming agent, multiplayer co-editing, Gemini 2.5 Flash backbone. So anything anyone wrote before yesterday about its limits — re-check.

13
00:05:54,560 --> 00:06:13,760
Gacrux: And it's still free. Three hundred and fifty generations per month per user. No card required. Bookmark it; don't subscribe. There's no subscription to subscribe to yet. ### 1.3 Google Flow — Veo 3.1 in a filmmaking shell

14
00:06:14,110 --> 00:06:53,430
Laomedeia: Flow is the cinematic-quality video generator backed by Veo 3.1 — Veo 3.1 Standard, Veo 3.1 Fast, and Veo 3.1 Lite. Veo 3.1 generates native audio inside the video — which means you don't need to layer a Suno or ElevenLabs track on top of your clips. Flow is the production environment for Veo: an Ingredients-to-Video feature lets you upload reference stills — old Rotary photographs, for example — and animate them. A Scenebuilder timeline keeps story continuity across clips without exporting to a separate editor.

15
00:06:53,780 --> 00:07:34,460
Umbriel: And here's where the price comes in. Google AI Pro — the tier you'd realistically use Flow on — is thirty-three Australian dollars a month. About fifty Veo 3.1 Fast clips per month at ten-eighty pee. Google AI Ultra is three hundred and thirty Australian dollars a month. Ten thousand to twenty-five thousand Flow credits. Clip length up to sixty seconds. Advanced camera controls. That's a serious subscription. For a one-off Rotary anniversary slideshow you do not need Ultra. You need Google AI Pro for the one month you're producing the slideshow.

16
00:07:34,810 --> 00:08:06,890
Zubenelgenubi: And — Zubenelgenubi here — let me put a clinical foot down. Flow doesn't have clinical accuracy controls. Veo will invent anatomy. It will invent drug packaging. It will invent equipment. So Flow is not a primary medical-illustration pipeline, and any patient-education micro-video you make with it needs senior clinician review before publication. ### 1.4 GPT-5.4 Thinking — the "Architecture" mode

17
00:08:07,240 --> 00:08:44,640
Gacrux: Here's what GPT-5.4 Thinking actually does. You give it a brief — say, "Write me a fifteen-minute Rotary talk for Thursday night on three things I'm building for Port Pirie." It generates a plan first. The plan is visible. You can edit it. You can say, "Move the SISU story to the end, lead with sepsis." And then it executes the plan. That two-step pattern is what's been called architect mode. It's a meaningful upgrade over GPT-5.3 Instant for any deliverable where the structure matters as much as the content.

18
00:08:44,990 --> 00:09:03,910
Umbriel: The slower-than-Instant trade-off is real. Don't use GPT-5.4 Thinking for quick lookups. Use it for plans. Slide decks. Posters. Pipeline specs. Talk scripts. Coroner reports. Discharge summaries where the structure is half the deliverable.

19
00:09:04,260 --> 00:09:28,860
Achird: And the price — ChatGPT Plus at about thirty Australian dollars a month with usage caps; ChatGPT Pro at three hundred and four dollars a month with unlimited five-point-four Thinking and five-point-four Pro. Most people, Jacob included, stay on Plus. ### 1.5 ChatGPT Images Two — gpt-image-2

20
00:09:29,210 --> 00:09:53,090
Zubenelgenubi: Now the one Jacob already uses. gpt-image-2. Snapshot `gpt-image-2-2026-04-21`. Released on the twenty-first of April. The Sepsis Poster Studio pipeline already calls this through Jacob's verified OpenAI organisation account. So this isn't should-I-adopt; this is what changed.

21
00:09:53,440 --> 00:10:17,040
Zubenelgenubi: What changed is that gpt-image-2 is the first agentic image model. It plans before it renders. It can run a web search during planning. That two-step pattern dramatically reduces anatomy errors and text errors compared to gpt-image-1. Output is up to two-kay resolution. Transparent backgrounds. Multi-image edits and inpainting.

22
00:10:17,390 --> 00:10:41,030
Zubenelgenubi: Pricing — per-image at one-zero-two-four by one-zero-two-four — low quality is about nine-tenths of a cent; medium is about eight cents; high quality is about thirty-two cents in Australian dollars. A high-quality poster panel will cost Jacob about a third of a dollar. For the Sepsis Studio pipeline, that's affordable.

23
00:10:41,380 --> 00:11:14,460
Umbriel: Two cautions. The organisation-verification gate is brittle — many users got stuck on Persona ID issues during the April rollout; Jacob already passed this so it's fine for him. And the model still hallucinates Australian-specific clinical detail — PBS packaging, SA Health branding, RACGP forms, RACP / RACMA letterheads. Human verification is mandatory. ### 1.6 Claude Design — the design system layer

24
00:11:14,810 --> 00:11:46,810
Laomedeia: Claude Design. Anthropic Labs. Seventeenth of April. Bundled with Claude Pro and above. Here's why it matters. You drop in your existing brand files — old Rotary newsletters, the Port Pirie regional logo, the SA Health colour palette — and Claude Design extracts a design system. Colours. Typography. Components. Layout patterns. Reusable. Every future deck you generate from that workspace inherits the system.

25
00:11:47,160 --> 00:12:17,840
Laomedeia: It builds interactive HTML prototypes, PPTX, PDF, standalone HTML, ZIPs. It can send to Canva. It accepts DOCX, PPTX, XLSX, and image inputs. It can scrape your website to pull brand elements. For a doctor in a regional hospital who needs deck after deck after deck — this is exactly the workflow that turns one-evening's design work into a year of consistent visual identity.

26
00:12:18,190 --> 00:12:32,870
Umbriel: PPTX export is semi-broken — that's the honest answer. Gradients drop; image crops shift. Treat Claude Design as the drafting layer and treat Keynote or PowerPoint as the finishing layer.

27
00:12:33,220 --> 00:12:59,020
Achird: Right. That's the five Jacob named. Two ambiguous names resolved — Architecture AI is GPT-5.4 Thinking, Claude Design is Anthropic Labs from April seventeenth. Stitch is for web mockups. Flow is for cinematic video. GPT-Image Two is the Sepsis Studio image API upgrade. Claude Design is the design-system layer. Now let's broaden out.

28
00:12:59,370 --> 00:13:19,810
Gacrux: Six tools. Adobe Firefly Image Four and Five. Midjourney v7. Ideogram v3. Black Forest Labs FLUX.2. Recraft V4. Leonardo AI. I'll give Laomedeia the floor on aesthetic decisions and Umbriel the sceptic role.

29
00:13:20,160 --> 00:13:31,720
Laomedeia: Let's start with the only tool in this wave that gives Jacob enterprise-grade legal indemnification. ### 2.1 Adobe Firefly — the indemnification layer

30
00:13:32,070 --> 00:13:54,590
Laomedeia: Adobe Firefly. firefly.adobe.com. Image Model Four, Image Model Four Ultra, Image Model Five — Five launched at MAX in October last year with native four-megapixel photorealism. Firefly Video is generally available, and in February of this year Adobe removed generation caps for paying subscribers.

31
00:13:54,940 --> 00:14:09,660
Laomedeia: The pricing — Firefly Standard is about fifteen Australian dollars a month. Firefly Pro is about forty-five. Firefly Premium is about three hundred and five with fifty thousand credits and unlimited video.

32
00:14:10,010 --> 00:14:47,970
Zubenelgenubi: And here's why I — speaking as the clinical voice — like Firefly. It's the only major model that provides enterprise IP indemnification. Adobe trained on licensed Stock content, public-domain material, and openly licensed work. They will legally defend paying users against infringement claims. That matters for any image destined for a Rotary newsletter, a SISU charity publication, a peer-reviewed clinical journal, or a coronial submission. If the image gets into the wild, you've got Adobe behind you. With Midjourney, Leonardo, Stable Diffusion derivatives — you don't.

33
00:14:48,320 --> 00:15:11,760
Umbriel: And here's why Firefly is not the only tool you need. Conservative content filters block legitimate clinical imagery — wounds, anatomy, IV access. The output ceiling is two-kay, so for A0 poster work you have to upscale externally. And anatomical accuracy lags Midjourney v7 and FLUX.2.

34
00:15:12,110 --> 00:15:36,230
Gacrux: The recommendation. Subscribe Firefly Standard at fifteen dollars a month for three months, and route any externally-published image through Firefly first. Forty-five dollars over the next quarter to remove legal risk from charitable and clinical work — that's a clear yes. ### 2.2 Midjourney v7 — the aesthetic monster

35
00:15:36,580 --> 00:16:05,380
Laomedeia: Midjourney v7. Best-in-class aesthetic quality. Cinematic lighting, painterly atmosphere, considered colour grading. For Rotary heritage-style imagery — the brassy, dusk-lit, evocative seventy-year retrospective frames — v7 is the right hammer. Anatomical accuracy is up about forty percent over v6. Eighty-five to ninety percent on simple hand poses.

36
00:16:05,730 --> 00:16:43,930
Umbriel: Three problems. One — the default "Midjourney look" is strong. Every image leans filmic or painterly unless you force `--style raw`. That's the wrong default for neutral clinical handouts. Two — text rendering is poor. Thirty to forty percent accuracy. Useless for poster overlays without external typesetting. Three — no commercial indemnification. And there's no public API. Which means Midjourney cannot be the Sepsis Studio image layer. It's a personal subscription tool only.

37
00:16:44,280 --> 00:17:03,880
Laomedeia: For the slideshow, though — for the one or two hero shots in the RCPP-Seventy that need to feel like a film still — Midjourney Standard, forty-five Australian a month, one month during the production window. That's the right buy. ### 2.3 Ideogram v3 — the text layer

38
00:17:04,230 --> 00:17:30,190
Gacrux: Here's the model that solves the text problem. Ideogram v3. Ninety to ninety-five percent accuracy on embedded typography. Correct kerning. Correct ligatures. Multi-line layouts. Versus Midjourney's thirty to forty percent. This is the difference between a poster that says "70 YEARS OF SERVICE" and a poster that says "7O YERSAS OF SERVUCE."

39
00:17:30,540 --> 00:17:46,020
Laomedeia: Free tier — ten generations a day. Basic at twelve Australian dollars a month. Plus at thirty dollars a month with API access. For any slide, handout, or poster that has embedded text, this is the layer.

40
00:17:46,370 --> 00:18:05,690
Umbriel: Limits. Anatomical accuracy is only average — not the right tool for surgical or pathology imagery. Stylistic range is narrower than Midjourney; outputs can feel "design-y" rather than photographic. Curved text paths and extreme perspective distortion still fail.

41
00:18:06,040 --> 00:18:22,840
Zubenelgenubi: So pair it. Ideogram for the text layer. Something else — gpt-image-2 or FLUX.2 — for the photo layer underneath. That's the synergy thesis showing up again. ### 2.4 FLUX.2 — open weights on Apple Silicon

42
00:18:23,190 --> 00:18:48,590
Gacrux: Black Forest Labs FLUX.2. This is the most interesting infrastructure story in the image cluster. The family includes max, pro, flex, dev, and klein variants. The dev and klein variants are Apache 2.0 open weights. Which means Jacob can pull them down to his MacBook and run them locally. Free after model download. No data leaves his device.

43
00:18:48,940 --> 00:19:05,580
Laomedeia: Quality-wise — twenty-twenty-six gold standard for text-in-image embedded in physical scenes. Big jump in anatomy and material texture — faces, hands, fabrics ahead of FLUX.1 and competitive with Midjourney v7.

44
00:19:05,930 --> 00:19:32,010
Zubenelgenubi: And for the Sepsis Studio, this is where it gets clinically interesting. Local execution means no PHI ever leaves the M-series MacBook. The `mflux` library on PyPI gives you a native Apple MLX port. On an M3 Max or M4, the klein four-billion-parameter variant fits in about thirteen gigabytes of VRAM and runs end-to-end on the laptop.

45
00:19:32,360 --> 00:19:47,440
Umbriel: It's five to ten times slower than an RTX 4090. Text rendering degrades beyond about ten words — for poster-length copy still use Ideogram. And the [max] tier is not open-weights; that's still BFL-hosted.

46
00:19:47,790 --> 00:20:06,590
Gacrux: Net — FLUX.2-dev or klein locally on the Mac for cost-and-privacy; FLUX.2-pro hosted via OpenRouter for quality; Ideogram for any text overlay. ### 2.5 Recraft V4 — the vector layer

47
00:20:06,940 --> 00:20:27,780
Laomedeia: Recraft V4. Only mainstream model that produces true editable SVG. Scalable to A0 poster size without resolution loss. Outputs open cleanly in Illustrator or Affinity. Brand Kit retains uploaded colour palettes, fonts, and reference style across all generations.

48
00:20:28,130 --> 00:20:51,490
Laomedeia: For Jacob this matters for one specific thing. Conference posters. A clinical poster is a layered artefact — central illustration, embedded text, plus an icon and flow-diagram layer. Recraft is the icon and flow-diagram layer. It outputs SVG that scales to A0 with no upscaling artefacts.

49
00:20:51,840 --> 00:21:06,200
Umbriel: Photorealistic humans is its weakest area — not suitable for clinical photography. Precise local edits still require reprompting. Complex multi-layered medical diagrams need manual cleanup.

50
00:21:06,550 --> 00:21:21,190
Achird: Recraft for icons and vectors. Plus tier — twenty-five US dollars a month — about thirty-eight Australian. For poster work, not for slides. ### 2.6 Leonardo AI — the all-rounder

51
00:21:21,540 --> 00:21:45,380
Gacrux: Last in the image cluster. Leonardo Phoenix 2.0. Cheap entry tier — eighteen Australian dollars a month. Hands and teeth materially improved — the so-called "spooky hands" problem largely solved. Custom model training — upload twenty Rotary historical photographs or your own clinical sketches to enforce style consistency.

52
00:21:45,730 --> 00:22:01,450
Umbriel: No commercial indemnification. Training data sources are not as airtight as Adobe's. Treat clinical-publication use cautiously. Anatomy still breaks under complex poses. No standout text rendering.

53
00:22:01,800 --> 00:22:14,040
Achird: Leonardo is fine. It's not the first choice for any of Jacob's specific use-cases. It's the second-or-third choice everywhere. So unless he loves the custom-model feature, skip it.

54
00:22:14,390 --> 00:22:27,110
Achird: Video. We've already covered Google Flow, which sits at the top of the cinematic-quality table. What else is in the field? ### 3.1 Runway Gen-4.5

55
00:22:27,460 --> 00:22:47,820
Laomedeia: Runway Gen-4.5. Currently number one on the Artificial Analysis text-to-video leaderboard — twelve hundred and forty-seven Elo. Best general motion fidelity for cinematic B-roll. Standard at eighteen Australian a month; Pro at forty-three; Unlimited at one hundred and sixteen.

56
00:22:48,170 --> 00:23:02,930
Umbriel: Ten-second hard clip ceiling — longer B-roll needs stitched extensions, which raises continuity risk. Gen-4.5 burns twenty-five credits per second. That gets expensive fast on a heavy iteration day.

57
00:23:03,280 --> 00:23:33,280
Zubenelgenubi: No medical training corpus. Anatomical motion — gait, respiration, wound healing — frequently hallucinates. Use only for stylised narrative framing, never as clinical reference. And the terms of service permit using uploads for product improvement on lower tiers — so do not upload patient photos or unconsented Rotarian portraits. ### 3.2 Kling 2.6 Pro

58
00:23:33,630 --> 00:24:04,550
Laomedeia: Kling 2.6 Pro. Best-in-class realistic human motion. Gait, gesture, micro-expression. Native audio in 2.6 Pro removes a separate sound-design step. Pay-per-second on fal.ai — no subscription. About eleven cents Australian per second with audio off; about twenty-six cents Australian per second with native audio and voice control. A five-second audio-on clip is about one Australian dollar.

59
00:24:04,900 --> 00:24:17,780
Achird: For Jacob this Thursday — if he wanted a five-second cinematic opener for Thursday night's talk, sign up to fal.ai, generate three clips, total cost under five dollars, done in an evening.

60
00:24:18,130 --> 00:24:36,770
Zubenelgenubi: But. Kling actively filters healthcare prompts. Anatomically accurate clinical demos are essentially impossible. So Kling for non-clinical short cinematic openers — yes. Kling for Sepsis Studio Stage 9 — no. ### 3.3 Pika 2.2

61
00:24:37,120 --> 00:25:03,440
Laomedeia: Pika 2.2 — and 2.5 generally available now too. Two features matter for Jacob's seventieth-anniversary slideshow. Scene Ingredients — you upload a person, a background, and an object as separate references and Pika composites them. Pikaframes — define first and last keyframes; Pika interpolates the in-between for smooth one-to-ten-second transitions.

62
00:25:03,790 --> 00:25:29,870
Laomedeia: Pikaframes is exactly the seventieth-anniversary brief. Cross-fade a 1956 photograph to a 1996 photograph to a 2026 photograph. Smooth. Cinematic. About forty-three Australian dollars for one month of Pika Pro — that's the recommendation. One month of Pika Pro covers the entire RCPP-Seventy production window.

63
00:25:30,220 --> 00:25:49,940
Umbriel: Short-form by design — not built for fifteen-minute narrative arcs. Clinical accuracy risk same as Runway. Scene Ingredients explicitly invites face uploads — never upload patient images. ### 3.4 Higgsfield, Krea — and the open-weights cluster

64
00:25:50,290 --> 00:25:59,090
Gacrux: Two more cloud tools and then I want to spend serious time on the open-weights cluster, because that's where the Sepsis Studio future lives.

65
00:25:59,440 --> 00:26:15,240
Gacrux: Higgsfield AI. Soul ID — train a persistent character identity from twenty-plus photos in five minutes, then reuse across many videos with consistent face, expression, lighting. Industry-leading character lock.

66
00:26:15,590 --> 00:26:39,590
Zubenelgenubi: Identifiable-person risk is the headline issue with Higgsfield. Soul ID is explicitly a face-clone tool. The terms of service shift consent burden to the user; uploads may train future models. Do not upload Rotarians, patients, or staff without written consent. In a clinical governance setting, the biometric framing is a hard sell. Avoid for now.

67
00:26:39,940 --> 00:27:00,020
Laomedeia: Krea AI — real-time canvas; sketch, drag, slide, and Krea re-renders in about fifty milliseconds. Aggregates Veo, Sora, Kling, Wan, Runway. Useful for storyboarding live during a planning session. Pro tier is fifty-three Australian a month.

68
00:27:00,370 --> 00:27:21,570
Umbriel: Free tier is now heavily restricted. Inherits the same hallucination problems as its underlying models. The upscaler will sharpen incorrect anatomy as confidently as correct anatomy. ### 3.5 Open weights — Mochi, Hunyuan, LTX-2.3, Wan 2.2

69
00:27:21,920 --> 00:27:34,720
Gacrux: The open-weights video cluster is where I want to spend a couple of minutes because this is the answer to Sepsis Studio Stage 9 — the video stage currently stubbed pending the SANA-WM weights verdict.

70
00:27:35,070 --> 00:28:26,350
Gacrux: Four candidates. Genmo Mochi 1 — Apache 2.0, ten-billion params, four-eighty pee at thirty frames per second, up to five-point-four seconds per clip. Tencent HunyuanVideo — custom community licence with EU, UK, and South Korea carve-outs. Lightricks LTX-2 and LTX-2.3 — LTX-2.3 from the fifth of March is Apache 2.0 with unrestricted commercial use, native four-kay at fifty fps, clips to twenty seconds, designed for consumer GPUs. Alibaba Wan 2.2 — also Apache 2.0, 1.3-billion variant runs on eight gigabytes of VRAM, confirmed working on M3 Max and M4 MacBooks via ComfyUI with GGUF quantised models.

71
00:28:26,700 --> 00:28:43,340
Zubenelgenubi: Strengths of the cluster — zero per-second cost after download; full data sovereignty for any clinical work; Apache 2.0 licences on Wan and LTX-2.3 permit redistribution, fine-tuning, and commercial use without revenue caps.

72
00:28:43,690 --> 00:29:10,250
Umbriel: Limitations of the cluster — quality gap below Veo 3.1, Gen-4.5, and Kling 2.6 on motion fidelity. Setup tax — ComfyUI plus GGUF plus custom-node configuration is an evening-long install; not a Thursday-deadline solution. Clinical accuracy risk persists — open weights don't fix medical hallucinations.

73
00:29:10,600 --> 00:29:38,200
Gacrux: Recommendation. If SANA-WM weights have not landed by the Sepsis Studio Stage 9 deadline — default to LTX-2.3 locally. Apache 2.0. Twenty-second clips. Four-kay output. Runs on Apple Silicon. And keep pay-per-second Kling 2.6 Pro via fal.ai as the cinematic-quality fallback for any one-off launch clip that doesn't contain patient context.

74
00:29:38,550 --> 00:30:01,830
Achird: Deck builders. Seven of them. Gamma. Beautiful.ai. Tome. Decktopus. Plus AI for Google Slides. Microsoft Designer plus Copilot in PowerPoint. Canva Magic Studio. Let me start with the one Jacob already pays for. ### 4.1 Gamma — what's changed

75
00:30:02,180 --> 00:30:25,860
Laomedeia: Gamma 3.0 lineage with a March-twenty-twenty-six image-generation refresh. The Agent now rewrites tone, restyles whole decks, and accepts long-form input. Studio Mode on Pro and Ultra ships premium image models — Flux family and Nano-Banana Pro. Image generation is genuinely better in twenty-twenty-six than it was six months ago.

76
00:30:26,210 --> 00:30:43,770
Laomedeia: For the seventieth-anniversary slideshow draft and the Thursday talk — Gamma is the right drafting layer. Plus tier at about twelve Australian a month for the Thursday talk. Pro tier at about twenty-three Australian a month if you want Studio Mode for the seventieth-anniversary deck.

77
00:30:44,120 --> 00:31:14,640
Umbriel: PPTX export flattens interactive cards, expandable sections, and embedded media. Typography defaults skew small and modern — for an older Rotary audience in a Port Pirie venue you must manually bump body text and contrast in Keynote afterwards. Credit-metered image generation — a thirty-slide heritage deck with several regenerations can chew through Plus-tier credits. ### 4.2 Beautiful.ai, Tome, Decktopus

78
00:31:14,990 --> 00:31:17,390
Gacrux: Three I'll cover briefly.

79
00:31:17,740 --> 00:31:31,780
Gacrux: Beautiful.ai — outline-first generation, Smart Slides auto-layout. Eighteen Australian a month on Pro. Corporate by default. Not the right tone for a Rotary heritage moment.

80
00:31:32,130 --> 00:31:58,490
Gacrux: Tome. Important to say clearly. Tome shut down its AI presentation product in April twenty-twenty-five. The founders pivoted into Lightfield. Anything anyone is recommending Tome for for presentations in twenty-twenty-six is working from stale information. If Jacob has any old Tome decks sitting in a legacy account, export them to PDF now before access goes dark.

81
00:31:58,840 --> 00:32:28,760
Gacrux: Decktopus — twenty-three Australian a month for Pro AI. Image quality is the weakest in the comparison set. Less projection-friendly than Gamma — default font sizes are small and accent colours often fail WCAG contrast against light backgrounds. For an older Rotary audience this is a real issue. Skip for RCPP-Seventy. ### 4.3 Plus AI and Copilot — the governance layer

82
00:32:29,110 --> 00:32:52,750
