00:43:02,710 --> 00:43:22,590
Gacrux: This is the thesis of the entire episode. Modern clinical posters are layered artefacts. A photo-realistic central illustration. Embedded text labels and call-outs. A vector icon set or flowchart. No single image model in May twenty-twenty-six does all three layers well.

107
00:43:22,940 --> 00:43:55,900
Gacrux: So you pipe each layer through its specialist. gpt-image-2 for the central illustration. Ideogram v3 for any text-heavy block. Recraft V4 for vector icons and flow diagrams. Compose in Canva Pro. This is the same pattern as a real medical illustrator's workflow — photographic plates plus typography plus diagrammatic icons — done with three APIs at about one Australian dollar per finished poster instead of four hundred for a freelancer.

108
00:43:56,250 --> 00:44:35,810
Zubenelgenubi: And it's not just cost. It's correctness. Each layer is rendered by the tool that's best at that layer. The result is more accurate than what any single tool would produce. Anatomy from gpt-image-2 because gpt-image-2 plans before it renders. Text from Ideogram because Ideogram's text accuracy is in the ninetieth percentile. Vectors from Recraft because Recraft is the only one outputting true SVG. Three specialists. Not one generalist. ### 6.3 Synergy three — local for privacy, cloud for cinematics

